-----------------------------------------------
File manifest:
-----------------------------------------------
- Helper Function folder
	- address_helper.cpp / .h  	--> handles addressing modes (PC/base/immediate)
	- hex_helper.cpp / .h      	--> handles hex parsing and formatting
	- obj_code.cpp / .h        	--> builds object code using bit-level manipulation
	- read_input.cpp / .h      	--> parses SIC input lines into structured data

- test_files folder
	- test_address_helper.cpp  	--> unit tests for address calculations
	- test_hex_helper.cpp      	--> unit tests for hex parsing/formatting
	- test_obj_code.cpp        	--> unit tests for object code generation
	- test_parser.cpp          	--> unit tests for input parsing

- main.cpp                   	--> entry point, runs pass1 and pass2
- Opcode_Dictionary.cpp / .h 	--> stores opcode formats and register mappings
- pass1.cpp / .h             	--> builds SYMTAB and intermediate listing file
- pass2.cpp / .h             	--> generates final object code listing
- README
- input_file.sic             	--> sample SIC/XE input file


----------------------------------------
Compile Instructions
----------------------------------------
To compile main file, navigate to project directory: 
	cd ~/a2
Then run:
	make clean (to make sure it wipes away old files)
then run:
	make
This will genereate the .exe file:
	lxe

To compile test files, navigate to test directory:
	cd ~/a2/test_files
Then run:
	make clean (make sure it wipes away old files)
then run:
	make
This will generate the .exe files:
	test_addr test_hex test_obj test_parser



---------------------------------------- 
Operating Instructions
----------------------------------------
To run main program:
	cd ~/a2
	./lxe input_file.sic

To run test programs:
	cd ~/a2/test_files
	./test_addr 
	./test_hex 
	./test_obj 
	./test_parser

Output Files:
- .l file: listing file containing addresses and final object code
- .st file: symbol table including labels and literal table

Notes:
- The program overwrites the .l file generated in pass1 with the final pass2 output
- Input files must follow SIC/XE formatting conventions

----------------------------------------
Design Decisions
----------------------------------------
Data structure decisions: we chose to use a hash table to implement our symtab and opcode table. This ensures easy lookups.

Bit Masking classes: instead of manual string manipulation for machine code, we used classes in obj_code.cpp
to set our NIXBPE bits, ensuring that our math is correct for the object code.

Literal Pool management: We implemented a safety net at the end of Pass1 to make sure that all literals would be handled and properly calculated before we reached the END.

Two Pass architecture: Pass 1 generaetes a symbol table and intermediate listing file while pass 2 is able to build off that draft listing file, 
calculate the machine code, and create the final listing file. 

We separated each part of our program into test_files and helper_functions and the main directory contains the pass1, pass2, and opcode table that we need. 
This ensures that we keep our codes neat and so we can locate certain features that we may need to fix. It ensures scalability and makes our code easier to read.

Modular Design: Each helper file focuses on a single responsibility (parsing, addressing, encoding), which improves debugging and maintainability.

Static Lookup Tables: Opcode and register mappings are implemented using static const hash tables to ensure fast lookup and prevent unnecessary reinitialization.

Intermediate File Strategy: Instead of storing all data in memory, we use a listing file between passes. This mimics real assembler design and simplifies debugging.

Error Handling: Basic validation is included (invalid opcodes, registers, addressing failures), with error messages printed to stderr.


-----------------------------------------
Bugs
-----------------------------------------
Edge Cases:
- Extremely large immediate values may exceed field size and trigger errors
- Input formatting must be consistent (tabs vs spaces) for proper parsing

-----------------------------------------
Lessons Learned
-----------------------------------------
Flag Logic: implementing how to incorporate NIXBPE flags and how to change from format 3/4

File I/O: building the intermediate files of .l and .st and ensuring that formatting stays compatible between compiler passes

Displacement: Understanding how to use LOCCTR and handling how to calculate displacement

Literal Table: Managing literal pools and ensuring literals are assigned addresses correctly, 
especially with LTORG and END handling

Testing Strategy: Writing separate unit tests for each helper module helped isolate bugs early 
and verify correctness incrementally


